{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "The move, a response to what conservatives consider left-leaning bias, has been criticized as an echo of the authoritarian past.", "abstract": "South Korean government announces that, beginning in 2017, it will require all middle and high school students to study history from government-issued textbooks; conservative supporters say current textbooks are ideologically biased against South Korea's past; opponents say move invokes North Korea's system and authoritarian regime of current president Park Geun-hye's father. ", "section_name": "World", "print_page": "9", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "Choe", "role": "reported", "lastname": "SANG-HUN", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}], "original": "By CHOE SANG-HUN"}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/13/world/asia/south-korea-to-issue-state-history-textbooks-rejecting-private-publishers.html", "lead_paragraph": "The move, a response to what conservatives consider left-leaning bias, has been criticized as an echo of the authoritarian past.", "headline": {"main": "South Korea to Issue State History Textbooks, Rejecting Private Publishers", "print_headline": "South Korea Orders State Control of History Textbooks"}, "_id": "561b9a6138f0d839bd91114f", "word_count": "770", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2015/10/13/world/13Korea-web/13Korea-web-thumbWide-v2.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2015/10/13/world/13Korea-web/13Korea-web-thumbWide-v2.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 401, "url": "images/2015/10/13/world/13Korea-web/13Korea-web-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2015/10/13/world/13Korea-web/13Korea-web-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "401"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}, {"height": 75, "url": "images/2015/10/13/world/13Korea-web/13Korea-web-thumbStandard-v2.jpg", "legacy": {"thumbnail": "image